<H3> <TI>   Alphandery Sees Economy Moving in `Right Direction' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Alphandery Sees Economy Moving in `Right Direction' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2504135094 Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES in French 25 Apr 94 
p 7 </F>

<F P=103> BR2504135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LA TRIBUNE DESFOSSES </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Blanca Riemer, special Washington correspondent: </F>
"Alphandery Vaunts French Economic Situation to G-7"] 
  [Excerpt] The finance ministers of the seven most highly 
industrialized countries (G-7), accompanied by the governors of 
their respective central banks, met late yesterday in Washington 
on the eve of the traditional spring meetings of the IMF and 
World Bank. Three main subjects were discussed: the problem of 
the increase in long-term interest rates in the wake of the 
gradual increase in interest rates in the United States; the 
question of how to follow up support to Russia following the 
IMF's financing worth 10 billion francs; and the functioning of 
the international capital markets. On his journey to 
Washington, French Economy Minister Edmond Alphandery once again 
expressed satisfaction at the French economic picture, which he 
was preparing to explain in detail to his interlocutors. 
  All the economic indicators in France "are moving in the 
right direction," Edmond Alphandery stressed, and the recovery 
is all the stronger because it is being led by all components of 
demand: better export performance, investment spending, the 
construction of houses, and household consumption. The economy 
minister thinks that the official growth forecasts of 1.4 
percent "now look rather cautious" to several economic bodies. 
"Some think that we should exceed that figure," he pointed out. 
To achieve that, three factors would have to be present: an 
increase in the rate of exports thanks to an improvement in the 
international environment; a stronger resumption of investment; 
and a rebuilding of stocks. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

