<H3> <TI>   Demilitarization Raised in Papandreou-Clinton Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Demilitarization Raised in Papandreou-Clinton Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2604085894 Nicosia I SIMERINI in Greek 26 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> NC2604085894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia I SIMERINI </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by K. Venizelos] </F>
  [Excerpt] In his recent meeting with President Bill 
Clinton, Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou raised 
President Glavkos Kliridhis' proposal to demilitarize Cyprus. 
According to informed sources, Papandreou did raise the Cypriot 
president's proposal but the U.S. side appears to insist on 
reaching an agreement for the confidence-building measures 
[CBM's]. President Clinton described the demilitarization 
proposal as "good" but untimely. 
  This fact creates the reasonable impression that the 
Americans will not renege on their efforts for an agreement on 
the CBM's, something that is also strengthened by reports that 
the Americans avoid discussing any alternate proposals such as 
those made by the Cypriot Government. Joe Clark's visit to the 
area is also linked with the UN intention to proceed with 
changes to the package. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

