<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark Accused of Attempting To Change CBM's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clark Accused of Attempting To Change CBM's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2504150394 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1400 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2504150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Joe Clark, UN secretary general's special 
representative in Cyprus, is attempting to bring changes to the 
21 March document for the confidence-building measures [CBM's]. 
This is the upshot of Clark's speech at the Carnegie Institute 
of Washington. 
  Commenting on Clark's speech, Government spokesman Ioannis 
Kasoulidhis said that the document accepted by the Greek Cypriot 
side refers only to the withdrawal of Turkish troops from the 
guard posts south of Famagusta and control of the road by the 
United Nations. 
  In his speech at the Carnegie Institute, Clark had said that 
the area that will be used for access to Famagusta could be used 
by the Turkish Cypriots, something that is not mentioned in the 
UN document. He had also said that with the confidence-building 
measures, Turkish Cypriots will have the right to travel by air 
to other countries and will also be able to charter flights to 
transfer passengers and cargo. Clark also had said that the UN 
asks various countries to give landing and take-off rights to 
one Turkish Cypriot airline. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

