<H3> <TI>   Vance-Papoulias Meeting on FYROM Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vance-Papoulias Meeting on FYROM Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2504203194 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 1800 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2504203194 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Roula Kambouriani from New York--live] </F>
  [Text] Ladies and gentlemen, good evening from New York, 
where these days there is very intense diplomatic activity in an 
attempt to lift the impasse in the Skopje [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] issue. Prime Minister Andreas 
Papandreou could possibly meet with UN Secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali on Wednesday [27 April]. On that same day, Foreign 
Minister Karolos Papoulias will have a meeting with 
Butrus-Ghali. Today, Foreign Minister Papoulias met with Cyrus 
Vance, UN special mediator on the Skopje issue. In the previous 
few days, Vance had meetings with Matthew Nimetz, U.S. envoy on 
the Skopje issue, and Skopean Foreign Minister Stevo 
Crvenkovski. Vance will again meet the Skopjean foreign 
minister in the coming days. Furthermore, Vance will meet 
Papoulias again before Thursday. 
  I expect goodwill moves from both sides, Vance said during 
his arrival for the meeting with Papoulias. Following are the 
remarks of the two men after their meeting, which lasted for one 
hour. 
  [Begin recording] [Kambouriani] Both Vance and Papoulias 
said that the effort will continue and that they are in 
continuous contact. When Vance was asked whether there will be 
an end to the impasse before the end of the week, he said: I do 
not want to guess when that will take place. Asked whether a 
new formula for a solution of the Skopje issue is being 
examined, Foreign Minister Papoulias said: 
  [Papoulias] Various proposals are under examination, but in 
general the effort centers on overcoming the impasse. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] Mr. Vance earlier talked about 
goodwill moves by both sides. What is your comment? 
  [Papoulias] Look, the position of the Greek Government is 
known and I think that Vance's goodwill services continue and 
this is the positive at this time. 
  [Kambouriani] Vance said that there are no plans for a 
meeting with Prime Minister Papandreou, and Papoulias ruled out 
a meeting, at this stage, with Skopjean counterpart Crvenkovski. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

