<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Discusses Cyprus With UN's Clark </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Discusses Cyprus With UN's Clark </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2504163494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1600 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2504163494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 25 (A.A.) -- Deputy Foreign Minister 
Ozdem Sanberk said Monday [25 April] that Turkey always 
supported the idea of overcoming confidence crisis between two 
communities on Cyprus. 
  Sanberk speaking before meeting with UN special envoy for 
Cyprus, Joe Clark, and his aides Gustave Feissel and John Paul 
Cavanaugh said Turkey always wanted a secure atmosphere to find 
a peaceful solution to Cyprus problem. 
  Recalling that the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus 
(TRNC) 
has accepted the points included to the original confidence 
building measures package of July 1993 and Turkey has supported 
this, Sanberk said the UN proposed package has been twisted 
after talks which began on February 17, 1994. 
  Clark told the press that the confidence building measures 
have reached a point and it would be a pity to stop it during 
this process. 
  Clark said he has met with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias in New York and is due to meet with Turkish officials 
in Ankara on Monday and Tuesday. 
  Clark called for a contribution from everybody. 
  `We arrived at this point with Turkey's active support and 
contributions,' Clark said. 
  He claimed that the TRNC would lose very important economic 
advantages if the process failed to succeed. 
  He also said the package will benefit both sides and the 
partial lifting of the embargo will strengthen the TRNC's 
economy by 20 percent. 
  The confidence building measures package has two points, one 
being the opening of the uninhabited Maras [Varosha] section for 
Greek settlement under UN supervision, and the other being the 
opening of the Lefkose [Nicosia] Airport also under UN direction 
and the partial lifting of the embargo imposed on the Turkish 
side. 
  The envoys will leave Turkey early Wednesday morning. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20086 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu080_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark, Sanberk Comment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clark, Sanberk Comment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2604065294 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
2000 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2604065294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy in Cyprus and former Canadian prime minister; his aide, 
Gustave Feissel; and John Paul Cavanaugh, a UN political aide, 
have been holding contacts in Ankara. [passage omitted] 
  After their meeting with Foreign Ministry Under Secretary 
Ozdem Sanberk, Clark said that mutual lack of trust remains the 
main problem in Cyprus. He pointed out that in the meeting, 
they discussed various points relating to the 
confidence-building measures [CBM's]. He said: One of the 
points was what specific advantages the Turkish Cypriot side can 
be given to balance the specific advantage the Greek Cypriots 
will get when they are allowed to resettle in Maras [Varosha]. 
Naturally, these advantages cannot be realized without an 
agreement. 
  In turn, Sanberk said that they exchanged views on the 
CBM's. 
He pointed out that he explained to Clark that the amendments 
made to the original version of the CBM's -- the one to which 
the Turkish Cypriots had agreed in principle -- substantially 
changed the basic spirit and parameters of the package. Sanberk 
went on to say that Clark expressed his views and briefed the 
Turkish side on the contacts he has held on the issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

