<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hurd Rejects Call for More UN Troops in Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hurd Rejects Call for More UN Troops in Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504171094 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1521 GMT 25 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2504171094 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Stephen Alderman, PRESS ASSOCIATION parliamentary staff] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd today rejected 
Opposition demands for more United Nations troops to be sent to 
war-torn Rwanda. Labour Foreign Affairs Spokesman Dr Kim 
Howells said 100,000 people had been slaughtered in the Central 
African country in the past two weeks. He asked why Britain had 
approved a UN decision to reduce peace-keeping troops there from 
2,700 to 270. "Is there one level of compassion for our 
European friends in Bosnia and another for black Africans?" 
  Brian Donohoe, Labour MP for Cunninghame South, protested 
the 
UN security force in Rwanda was doing "absolutely nothing." He 
demanded: "When is the Government going to put pressure on the 
UN to bring back the troops to safeguard the lives of those that 
are being slaughtered in that country today?" 
  Mr Hurd replied: "I am not sure how either of you suppose 
that maintaining a UN force at the original scale is going to 
help assuage these horrors." 
  The UN Security Council had concluded it was no longer 
possible for the UN force to carry out its mandate, he said. 
"I assure you there is no magic in keeping troops there, if 
there is not something useful which they can do." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

