<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Believes Serbs Will Comply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Believes Serbs Will Comply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604170894 Paris France-Inter Radio Network in French 1600 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2604170894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-Inter Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The decision to carry out air strikes against the 
Serbs should be taken in Brussels by the NATO command, which 
would need the UN green light. This afternoon the international 
community seems determined to make sure that this new ultimatum 
is respected, even if President Mitterrand thinks that it will 
be unnecessary to resort to air strikes. Francois Mitterrand 
was interviewed by Ralph Pinto in Tashkent, Uzbekistan: 
  [Begin Mitterrand recording] I believe that the UN forces 
are 
thinking that the ultimatum is going to be respected by the 
deadline. I have nothing else to add. My wish, naturally, is 
for military intervention to be avoided if it is not deemed 
necessary -- that is, if Serb forces and their positions conform 
to the conditions set by the international community. You will 
then be informed and so will I. 
  I hope that all this will be settled in a peaceful way, and 
that is why France took the initiative to call for the holding 
of an international conference -- and it is a good thing that it 
has been taken up by others. Unlike what happened in the past, 
this conference will be held parallel to the ultimatum and 
attended by at least the United States, Russia, and the EU 
[European Union] under the aegis of the United Nations. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

