<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA: DPRK Response `Not Fully Satisfactory' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA: DPRK Response `Not Fully Satisfactory' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2704114294 Paris AFP in English 1111 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2704114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, April 27 (AFP) -- North Korea Wednesday [27 
April] responded to conditions posed by the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) for inspection of one of its nuclear 
plants, but diplomatic sources close to the Agency said the 
response was not fully satisfactory. 
  The IAEA had set a series of conditions to the sending of 
inspectors to monitor the replacement of spent nuclear fuel rods 
at a five megawatt reactor at Yongbyon, a plant which the United 
States suspects of being used to produce nuclear weapons. 
  The North Korean "response is currently being examined by 
the 
IAEA services and we are in consultation with Agency member 
states," IAEA spokesman David Kyd said. 
  A diplomatic source close to the Agency said however that 
"the North Korean response might not be entirely satisfactory 
and it is practically ruled out that inspectors [will] leave 
(for Korea) before the end of the week." 
  Differences reportedly centred on how the spent fuel rods 
should be controlled, the source said. 
  "It is essential for the IAEA, that our inspectors be 
allowed 
to take samples of some of the spent fuel to prove that the 
North Koreans have not diverted any nuclear material for 
military ends. We want to be present during the whole period of 
the unloading of the reactor and we demand that all the spent 
fuel from the reactor be placed under the Agency's control," Kyd 
said. 
  The North Koreans have said they want to start unloading the 
reactor at the beginning of May and have consequently asked that 
the IAEA send inspectors as soon as possible. The whole 
operation should last about two months, Kyd said. 

</TEXT>

