<F P=100> UNITED KINGDOM </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukraine Exercises Surveillance Rights of `Open Skies' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine Exercises Surveillance Rights of `Open Skies' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404150294 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1517 GMT 24 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2404150294 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A Soviet-built plane will be spying over British 
military installations this week -- with the blessing of NATO. 
  Described as part of the Ukrainian Air Force, the Antonov 30 
will exercise its rights under the open skies treaty by carrying 
out surveillance sorties. 
  The treaty provides for various nations to fly over each 
others territory to gather intelligence using aerial 
photography, radar and video cameras. 
  It will be the first time an Antonov 30 from Ukraine is seen 
here as it flies over Lincolnshire to RAF Scampton on Thursday. 
  The Ukrainians will be hosted by a team from the Joint Arms 
Control Implementation Group, which is based at Scampton and has 
reciprocal arrangements for carrying out similar spying missions 
over former Iron Curtain countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

