<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Denies Deal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bonn Denies Deal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2704092394 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 0831 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2704092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- The German Government has rejected 
reports that the supply of German submarines to Taiwan, 
originally banned in early 1993, is to go ahead after all via a 
different route. A government spokesman said today in response 
to a query that Bonn has "no plans" to send Taiwan any 
submarines via a cooperation agreement with U.S. firms. 
  Contrary to usual practice, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl 
stated publicly following a secret meeting of the Federal 
Security Council on 28 January 1993 that delivery is out of the 
question as far as Bonn is concerned. This position has not 
changed. 
  According to reports published in the HANDELSBLATT and NEUE 
ZEIT, the submarine deal with Taiwan is supposed to be worth 
around 10 billion German marks [DM]. In addition, the supply of 
the submarines is intended to open the way for the sale of the 
German Intercity Express high-speed train, a deal worth a total 
of around DM30 billion. 

</TEXT>

