<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO Partnership Approval Likely Next Month </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO Partnership Approval Likely Next Month </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2604181194 Stockholm Radio Sweden in English 1615 GMT 26 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2604181194 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Swedish Defence Minister Anders Bjoerck says this 
neutral country is likely to join NATO's Partnership for Peace 
programme next month. Bjoerck says the centre right 
government's proposal to join the programme will probably pass 
through parliament with little or no opposition. But the 
defence minister adds, joining Partnership for Peace does not 
mean Sweden is abandoning its traditional neutrality. 
  Fourteen countries--all East European states and former 
Soviet republics--have so far signed up to join the scheme. 
Another neutral Nordic country, Finland, has also said it will 
join the programme. The other three Nordic countries--Denmark, 
Norway and Iceland--are already full members of NATO. 

</TEXT>

