<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank Governor Rejects Claims of Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bank Governor Rejects Claims of Money Laundering </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2604200594 Nicosia CyBC Television Network in Greek 1730 
GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2604200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia CyBC Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Central Bank Governor Avxendis Avxendiou 
categorically rejected a report in a French magazine that Cyprus 
is a transfer point of dirty money. Avxendiou stressed that the 
banking system in Cyprus is clean. Correspondent Petros 
Konstandinou has the following report: 
  [Begin recording] [Konstandinou] Cyprus' banking system has 
become a target in the foreign press. A report in the French 
magazine L'EXPRESS represents Cyprus as a transfer point for 
dirty money. Central Bank Governor Avxendiou categorically 
rejected the report and added that it is not the first time that 
something like this has happened. 
  [Avxendiou] I cannot rule out that there are isolated cases, 
but I reject the possibility and the claim that Cyprus is a 
point of systematic laundering of dirty money. 
  [Konstandinou] Have there even been isolated cases of which 
you are aware? 
  [Avxendiou] No, not even one case has come to our attention 
because if we become aware of something like this, you realize 
that the measures that we would take would be really drastic. 
  [Konstandinou] In order to safeguard the banking system, 
Avxendiou said, there is continuous and systematic control of 
both Cypriot and foreign banks. All officials of all banks, he 
said, have been given strict instructions to be very careful in 
their dealings. The banks have also been instructed not to open 
an account for anyone unless they first prove their identity. 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

