<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Erbakan Considers Cyprus Negotiations Unnecessary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Erbakan Considers Cyprus Negotiations Unnecessary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2704185394 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2704185394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Turkish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Prosperity Party [PP] leader Necmettin Erbakan has 
said that his party does not consider negotiations on the Cyprus 
issue necessary. If negotiations must be held, he said, they 
must be held only after the existence of two communities having 
equal rights is accepted. 
  Addressing PP deputies today, Erbakan said that the first 
thing to do is to strengthen the Turkish Republic of Northern 
Cyprus [TRNC] and to ensure that it is recognized. From the 
beginning, he said, we have been calling for the existence of 
two independent separate states on the island. 
  [Begin Erbakan recording] Everybody knows that we never 
cared for these negotiations from the beginning. We have only 
one problem in Cyprus and it is to ensure that the TRNC is 
recognized first by the Muslim countries and then by the entire 
world, then to help strengthen the TRNC and increase its 
prosperity. That is our only Cyprus problem. [end recording] 
  Erbakan said that if negotiations must be held, they must be 
held only after the equality of the two communities is accepted. 
The issues can be discussed separately in the negotiations, he 
said. 
  The PP leader pointed out that the United Nations has been 
defending the same principles for the past 15 years, but that 
since Butrus-Ghali became secretary general, the UN started to 
ask for concessions. Erbakan stressed that the Turkish Grand 
National Assembly rejected this stand both on 10 June and with 
its resolution yesterday. 
  On the economy, Erbakan said that inflation and foreign debt 
will increase fast and the growth rate drop. He said that for a 
solution either early elections or a new coalition is necessary. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

