<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Juppe Demands Release of Aid Workers Held in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Juppe Demands Release of Aid Workers Held in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2704172994 Paris AFP in English 1704 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2704172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Paris, April 27 (AFP) -- France "demands" the 
immediate and unconditional release of 11 aid workers held by 
Bosnian Serbs for more than two weeks on the outskirts of 
Sarajevo, Foreign Minister Alain Juppe said Wednesday [27 April]. 
  The 11 French aid workers, members of the "Premiere urgence" 
humanitarian group, were detained by Bosnian Serbs on April 8 on 
charges of trying to smuggle arms to Bosnian Moslems. 
  The workers "did their humanitarian duty and nothing else," 
the minister told parliament, adding that they had been "set 
up," with weapons purposefully put aboard their convoy. 
  Their arrest and detention in Bosnian Serb barracks followed 
a warning by the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation that it 
would bomb Bosnian Serb forces if they did not remove their 
heavy weapons from around Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

