<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN's Clark Arrives, Comments on Talks in Turkey </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN's Clark Arrives, Comments on Talks in Turkey </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2704152994 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1400 GMT 27 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2704152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
representative on Cyprus, arrived in Cyprus from Turkey this 
afternoon and will meet [Turkish Cypriot leader] Rauf Denktas at 
1800 this afternoon. 
  Speaking at Larnaca Airport on his arrival, Clark avoided 
announcing the Turkish stance on the 21 March document on ways 
of implementing the confidence-building measures. Replying to a 
series of questions from CyBC [Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] 
on the issue, Clark said that he did not expect Turkish 
authorities to explain their recent statements that they perhaps 
intended for someone else. He said he had the opportunity to 
deal with some wrong impressions that exist in Turkey, one of 
which is that there are two documents. There are not two 
documents but one and we will discuss ways to implement it. 
Clark also noted that the decision to accept or reject [the 
document] should be made by the two communities based on actual 
events. He also said that he will not present a new set of 
proposals. Asked about the purpose of his meeting tomorrow with 
President Glavkos Kliridhis, who has accepted the document, 
Clark answered that he will discuss ways of implementing the set 
of proposals that Kliridhis and Denktas have accepted in 
principle. Furthermore, Clark said that he would be surprised 
if a new extension is given for an answer from the Turkish side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

