<H3> <TI>   Vatican Proposes Peace Conference on Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vatican Proposes Peace Conference on Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2804105694 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1303 GMT 27 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2804105694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Vatican/Rwanda: Vatican Proposes </F>
International Peace Talks"] 
  [Text] (ANSA) Vatican City, April 27 -- The Vatican on 
Wednesday [27 April] asked that an international peace 
conference on Rwanda be organized, to be attended by the two 
rival tribes in the central African country, the heads of state 
of neighboring countries and the Western countries most involved 
or interested in the region's development. 
  The appeal was issued by the Vatican's "Cor Unum" Papal 
Council, which is headed by Roger Etchegaray and deals with 
relations between Catholic organizations and international aid 
bodies. 
  In its statement, the council also urged the international 
community "to intensify its presence in the field and diplomatic 
mediation, since one cannot remain indifferent or passive in the 
face of this genocide." 
  Cor Unum officials on April 25 met officials from about 30 
Catholic organizations and from the United Nations High 
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) to discuss ways and means of 
allowing relief aid to reach Rwandan refugees who are fleeing 
attacks from Hutu and Tutsi tribes. 
  "To understand the seriousness of the conflict," the 
Vatican's statement said, "one must remember that the largest 
exodus is taking place since the Gulf War, involving hundreds of 
thousands of people in flight. Victims are innumerable, 
especially among civilians." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

