<F P=100> BENELUX COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> The Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amsterdam, Brussels To Integrate Navies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amsterdam, Brussels To Integrate Navies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BR2804135594 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 27 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR2804135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>
<F P=105>  Dutch </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Peter de Graaf and Wio Joustra: "Netherlands and </F>
Belgian Navies To Integrate"] 
  [Excerpts] The Hague/Brussels -- The Navies of the 
Netherlands and Belgium are going to strengthen their 
cooperation. In the near future, there will be talk of an all 
but complete operational integration of the most important 
surface ships of the two navies. 
  The frigates and minehunters of both countries will then, in 
practice, comprise a single navy, although control of the ships 
will remain in national hands. The command center for the joint 
fleet will be in Den Helder, manned by military personnel from 
both countries. [passage omitted] 
  In The Hague there was talk Tuesday [26 April] that this was 
similar to the German-Netherlands Army Corps to be set up in 
Muenster. This corps will comprise two German divisions and one 
Netherlands division. The difference is that the 
German-Netherlands Corps will be under a revolving command. The 
Netherlands Navy commander will continue to be the primary 
person responsible for the joint navy with Belgium. [passage 
omitted] 
  The cooperation is designed mainly to produce military 
budget 
savings. The Netherlands Navy will have to reduce its personnel 
nearly 30 percent by the year 2000. With a total budget 
reduction of 18 percent since 1989 and considering that the 
Navy's budget accounts for some 20 percent of the overall 
defense budget, it is clear that there have been major savings 
in this branch of the Armed Forces over the past five years. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

