<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark Ends Talks on Confidence-Building Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clark Ends Talks on Confidence-Building Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Clark Departs </H4>

<F P=102> NC2904091794 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 0700 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2904091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Joe Clark, the UN secretary general's special 
envoy, has expressed his feeling that there will be consequences 
from the failure of the talks on the confidence-building 
measures and added that nobody can predict what these 
consequences will be. 
  Before leaving Cyprus this morning, Mr. Clark told CyBC 
[Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation] that in the end all the 
Cypriot people will pay the price for the failure of the talks. 
He noted that Rauf Denktas was very hasty in stating that the 
process had collapsed, and added that Denktas has ulterior 
motives for what he does and says. Mr. Clark added: I cannot 
say anything else except that Denktas intentionally and hastily 
said our efforts had collapsed. Mr. Clark said the United 
Nations must decide to continue its mission and to study 
seriously the suggestions he will submit later. 
  Mr. Clark also noted that there has not been enough good 
faith or political will to solve the problems. When asked what 
should be done to create such a will, he said that in addition 
to the two leaders in Cyprus there are other voices which should 
probably be encouraged to take a bigger part in the 
consultations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

