<H3> <TI>   KKE Official Comments on Cyprus, U.S. Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KKE Official Comments on Cyprus, U.S. Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2904092994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1500 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2904092994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] KKE [Greek Communist Party] Secretary General Aleka 
Papariga returned from her official visit to Cyprus, where she 
met with Cypriot President Glavkos Kliridhis and Cypriot party 
leaders. 
  In a statement issued on the Cyprus issue, Mrs. Papariga 
maintained that the United States, Britain, and Turkey are not 
interested in a specific way out of the problem. She noted: It 
is more to their benefit that Cyprus remain as it is, with a 
sort of a de facto partition, so they can intervene for their 
own interests in the region. Mrs. Papariga stressed that what 
we need in Greece today is pressure on the government to change 
its direction on the Cyprus issue. 
  Commenting on Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's meetings 
in 
the United States on the Cyprus issue, Mrs. Papariga said: 
Alas, if we stay with President Clinton's assurances, 
particularly when we know his more general [words indistinct] 
role in the Balkans. 

</TEXT>

