<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clark Ends Talks on Confidence-Building Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clark Ends Talks on Confidence-Building Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `No Agreement' Reached </H4>

<F P=102> NC2804151294 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1030 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2804151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>

<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] At noon today, Joe Clark, the UN secretary 
general's special representative in Cyprus, said that no 
agreement has been reached on the confidence-building measures 
and that there is no reason for further talks with the two 
sides, at least today. He said: After my meeting today with 
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktas, I do not think there is any 
reason for me to hold any more talks. 
  In a statement at the Ledra Palace checkpoint, Clark said 
that before making any suggestions, he wants to think about what 
he discussed here and in his meetings with Greek and Turkish 
representatives. Asked if he suggested any changes to the 21 
March UN document, Clark said: I only dealt with one 
suggestion. We always had just one package, nothing more, and 
the issue was how to implement it. I asked that we deal with it 
imaginatively. We have worked on it but reached no agreement. 
  Clark and Gustave Feissel, the UN secretary general's 
alternate special representative in Cyprus, will brief the 
ambassadors of the five UN Security Council permanent members on 
their meetings in Nicosia and Ankara. The meeting will be held 
at 1800 today at the British High Commission. Clark will leave 
Cyprus at 0800 tomorrow. [passage omitted] 
  In answer to a question, government spokesman Ioannis 
Kasoulidhis said it seems that the new UN effort has reached a 
deadlock. He said that our side is now waiting for the UN 
secretary general to submit his report, which would recount the 
events and should attribute responsibilities where they exist. 
Asked whether Clark will have a new meeting with the president, 
Kasoulidhis said the UN envoy wished the president Happy Easter 
and bade him farewell. He added that if anything comes up, the 
president will never refuse to meet with Clark. 
  After meeting Kliridhis, Clark said he had a lengthy meeting 
with the president, adding that there is no reason for further 
comment in view of the new meeting with Denktas. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-20297 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu083_p_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-083 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Papandreou Meets Butrus-Ghali, Comments on UN Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Papandreou Meets Butrus-Ghali, Comments on UN Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2804211894 Athens ET-1 Television Network in Greek 2030 
GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2804211894 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens ET-1 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Consultations on Skopje [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Yugoslavia--FYROM] continued today at the top level 
in UN Headquarters, where Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou met 
with the UN secretary general. Our New York special 
correspondent Roula Kambouryianni reports. 
  [Begin recording] [Kambouryianni] No specific positive 
developments can be discerned on the Skopje issue. However, UN 
Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali did not ask for Security 
Council intervention, and the mediation effort by Cyrus Vance is 
continuing. This is what Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou said 
after his 40-minute meeting with Butrus-Ghali in the presence of 
Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias and Mr. Cyrus Vance. Before 
the meeting, Mr. Butrus-Ghali held consultations both with Mr. 
Vance and with Matthew Nimetz, State Department special 
coordinator on the Skopje issue. 
  In addition to the Skopje question, the Cyprus and Bosnian 
issues were also discussed. As the prime minister said, however, 
we did not touch on matters of substance. After the failure of 
the talks on the confidence-building measures, the Greek side 
expressed its regret for the deadlock in the Cyprus issue 
because of the Turkish intransigence. 
  [Papandreou] We expressed our regret for the course of the 
Cyprus issue. There have already been 20 years of occupation, 
and the process should change so that we end with a solution 
acceptable to the people of Cyprus, a solution that will be just 
and lasting. 
  [Kambouryianni] Responding to a Turkish correspondent's 
question on relations with Turkey, the prime minister said that 
we hope they will improve, and we are doing all we can in this 
direction. 
  Coming out of UN Headquarters, Mr. Vance described the 
meeting as very positive. He said: We have cooperated with Mr. 
Papandreou in the past; let us hope that progress will be made 
soon. The prime minister and members of the Greek delegation 
will leave for Athens today. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

